@article{Yao2021_AT2019wey_i,
abstract = {The Galactic low-mass X-ray binary AT2019wey (ATLAS19bcxp, SRGA J043520.9+552226, SRGE J043523.3+552234, ZTF19acwrvzk) was discovered as a new optical transient in Dec 2019, and independently as an X-ray transient in Mar 2020. In this paper, we present comprehensive NICER, NuSTAR, Chandra, Swift, and MAXI observations of AT2019wey from $\sim$1 year prior to the discovery to the end of September 2020. AT2019wey appeared as a $\sim$1 mCrab source and stayed at this flux density for several months, displaying a hard X-ray spectrum that can be modeled as a power-law with photon index Gamma$\sim$1.8. In June 2020 it started to brighten, and reached $\sim$20 mCrab in $\sim$2 months. The inclination of this system can be constrained to i<$\sim$30 deg by modeling the reflection spectrum. Starting from late-August ($\sim$59082 MJD), AT2019wey entered into the hard-intermediate state (HIMS), and underwent a few week-long timescale outbursts, where the brightening in soft X-rays is correlated with the enhancement of a thermal component. Low-frequency quasi-periodic oscillation (QPO) was observed in the HIMS. We detect no pulsation and in timing analysis of the NICER and NuSTAR data. The X-ray states and power spectra of AT2019wey are discussed against the landscape of low-mass X-ray binaries.},
